: Opaque Windows in Vilhelm Hammershøi’s Interior Paintings -- tRilke’s Magic Lantern: Figural Language and the Projection of “Interior Action” in the Rodin Lecture -- tTouch Screen: Skin as a Shifter between Body, Space, and Image in the Work of Birgit Jürgenssen -- tWild Walls, Revolving Sets, Built Cuts: Staged Interiors in Contemporary Photography and Film Installation -- tPolitics and Ethics -- tGerhard Richter’s Tisch: Memory Images and German Disavowal in 1962 -- tAndrea Zittel’s “Small Liberties”: Siting Interiors in the Current Media Landscape -- tUnbelonging Interior: Chantal Akerman’s Là-bas -- tContributors -- tPicture Credits -- tIndex -- tPlates0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book explores the historical connections between the notions of architectural interior, subjective space, human interiority, and represented space including virtual space.In the 18th century the notion of "interiority" understood as a paradigm of human subjectivity came to be articulated in a sustained way in architectural and visual, rather than only literary forms. While the notion of the interior and the processes of "interiorization" were, as Walter Benjamin demonstrated, the defining features of 19th-century bourgeois culture, it is the different forms of conceptual assault on, or deconstruction of interiority that define the approach to space and self in the 20th and 21st centuries. The book examines models of understanding "interiority" as these were developed in relation to notions of space and spatial experience.  aVeranschaulichungsformen von Innerlichkeit finden in der Moderne in Darstellungen des Interieurs ihr prägnantes Bild. Die Beiträger der Publikation untersuchen die Verbindungen zwischen architektonischen Innenräumen, visuellen und literarischen Darstellungen von Interieurs und dem Konzept der Innerlichkeit vom 18. Jahrhundert bis heute.Jene Darstellungen sind Effekt, aber auch Produzenten spezifischer Vorstellungen von Innerlichkeit als einer, wenn nicht der subjektkonstituierenden Praxis der Moderne.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIdentity (Psychology) in architecturexHistory. 0aInterior architecturexHistory. 0aSpace (Architecture)xHistory. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh1 aBrons, Franziska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchloh, Benjamin H. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiekmann, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoherty, Brigid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrave, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrögel, Katrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaverkamp, Anselm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHellman, Mimi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHemkendreis, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJollet, Etienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlonk, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhn, Holger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLajer-Burcharth, Ewa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLajer-Burcharth, Ewa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPark, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchuldenfrei, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca